A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: 30 Jun 2011
From: Ramon Noseda <rnoseda@laboratorioazul.com.ar> [edited]


Bovine anthrax -- Buenos Aires, Argentina
-----------------------------------------
An estancia [cattle ranch] in General Alvear Province, Buenos Aires,
lies amidst the rich soils of Cuenca del Rio Salado, the archetypal
area for cattle breeding. The outbreak occurred in an unvaccinated
herd of 280 2-year-old heifers, one of which suddenly died. There was
an exsanguination of blood from the natural orifices, and on opening
the abdomen the veterinarian noted a marked splenomegaly; a sample
cultured positive for _Bacillus anthracis_.

Antibiotic sensitivity was noted to Penicillin, Ampicillin,
Ciprofloxacin, Florfenicol, Tetracycline, Tilmicocin and Gentamicin,
and resistance to Trimethoprim. The herd was vaccinated with Sterne
vaccine.

The estancia has a history of more than 40 years of anthrax
outbreaks. The carcass had been attacked by 'Chimangos' or caracaras
(_Milvago chimango_)[hawks]. The recovery of anthrax spores from
their faeces in the Province of Santa Fe is described in a 2007 paper.
[Miguel D. Saggese, Ramon P. Noseda, Marcela M. Uhart, Sharon L. Deem,
Hebe Ferreyra, Marcelo C. Romano, Maria C. Ferreyra-Armas & Martin
Hugh-Jones, 2007. First detection of _Bacillus anthracis_ in feces of
free ranging raptors from central Argentina, _Journal of Wildlife
Diseases_, 43: 136-141.] The carcass was immediately buried.

