[Unfortunately a characteristic history. It is proving very difficult
to persuade the estancieros to routinely vaccinate their stock in this
part of Argentina, where the black steppe/pampas soil is perfect for
spore survival. So each year they get a number of outbreaks, virtually
always on ranches with unvaccinated stock. The cost of the resulting
dead stock far exceeds the trivial cost of Sterne vaccine.

One will only find anthrax spores in the faeces of scavenger birds
when they have been feeding on carcasses that had been open for a
couple of days -- this allows the necessary access to air and time for
sporulation. Vegetative cells will not survive passage through the
bird's stomach, and thus after feeding on freshly dead animals their
faeces are normally without spores. In Texas, where I do most of my
fieldwork, the caracaras, beautiful though they are, are not as
aggressive as the Turkey buzzards that can gut a whitetail deer in
minutes of it dying. So the Texas caracaras manage with roadkill and
small dead animals.

For a description of the chimango, go to:
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chimango_Caracara
For pictures:
http://search.aol.com/aol/image?q=chimango&v_t=comsearch50
http://www.oiseaux.net/birds/photos/chimango.caracara.html
Caracas comprise some 5 genera; the Northern Caracara (_C. cheriway_)
is found in Texas, Arizona, and Florida. See:
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caracara

To find General Alvear province, go to:
http://www.fallingrain.com/world/AR/01/General_Alvear.html -
Mod.MHJ]
